ancient Germanic <i>Adalgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gaira-</i> ‘lance, spear’, or <i>Albgari</i>, with the first element <i>alb</i> ‘elf’. Compare   Auge  ,   Oge  ,   Ogea  , and   Osier  .","English: variant of   Alger  ."]},{"name":"Algar","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Algar</i>, representing the falling together of two Old English names, <i>Ælfgār</i> and <i>Æthelgār</i>, composed of the elements respectively <i>ælf</i> ‘elf’ or <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gār</i> ‘spear’. It could also be from the much rarer Old English personal name <i>Ealdgār</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘old’ + ‘spear’. In East Anglia, it is more probably a variant of   Alger   (Old Norse <i>Álfgeirr</i>). See also   Agar  ,   Elgar  ."]},{"name":"Alker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Gerhart.","South German: variant of   Alger  .","English: habitational name from Altcar, Lancashire. This name means ‘marshland by the River Alt’, from Old Norse <i>kjarr</i> ‘marsh’ and the river name <i>Alt</i>."]},{"name":"Ager","meanings":["English (mainly Essex, Suffolk, and Northamptonshire): variant of   Alger   or possibly of   Edgar  .","Danish: habitational name from any of several places called Ager, meaning ‘plowed land’ (from a cognate of the English word <i>acre</i>).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Adgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gari</i> (from <i>garwa</i>) ‘ready, eager’ or <i>gari</i> ‘spear’. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Alger was born in 1313, in Lindsell, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Alger, was 20 and his mother, Mrs John Alger, was 18. He had at least 1 son with Mrs John Alger. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1313–":"1313–Surnud","1313–Male":"1313–Surn